This PR is related to #383.
It fixes part of the second issue in #383, but not the whole thing.
When I send a password reset request and click the link, this app is now able to handle it.
However, when I send a magic login request and click that link, this app does the same thing (shows you the password reset form).
It's because there doesn't seem to be any way to distinguish these two redirect links - both of them have type=recovery in them. Anyway, I'd be happy to look into the backend if it helps.

What kind of change does this PR introduce?
Trying to emulate localStorage which is synchronous with AsyncLocalStorage in the Expo example. It's not the most elegant solution but it should do the job.
What is the current behavior?
Supabase relies on localStorage but and does not expect it to return a promise, which causes that Supabase is not able to get values from the storage (e.g. auth).
What is the new behavior?
Emulated storage retrieves all keys from the AsyncLocalStorage and stores them locally, so they can be accessed synchronously. Also, it pauses the rendering of the App until the storage is ready and SupabaseClient can be initialized. Additionally, I've disabled detecting of the session in the URL because window.location is not available in Expo.

What kind of change does this PR introduce?
This PR is a current draft for a RedwoodJS Quickstart guide.
It is a work in progress, and will be followed up with an example repo that people can use.
Note. This example stays true to the other Quickstart guides, but is not typically how one would create a Redwood app.
It relies on all client web side interaction with Supabase for fetching profiles etc.
However, Prisma has some shortcomings that make this quick start impractical to do:

it cannot introspect or use cross schema foreign keys. That is the profile user id cannot link to the auth.users table.
RLS on the Redwood api side is not possible with Prisma because it cannot set the auth user's token in the transaction
While I could have rewritten the guide to use the Supabase client on the api side, still use GraphQL for profile fetching and mutation, this felt like more an exercise in learning Redwood that Supabase. Though, these should still be authored and added as "advanced" examples.

So, we'll just use Supabase from the web side, which is perfectly fine. This example still leverages Redwood's Supabase auth integration and all the useAuth() hooks for sign in/out and determining if your user is logged in.
And the token is still verified on the API side via the JWT_SECRET and the Supabase decoder.

What is the current behavior?
OSS page and txt files return 404.

txt files had rewrite rule set up in next.config.js, but since the rewrite path is not on the same next.js app, the rule was ignored, hence returning 404.
OSS page did not have any rewrite or redirect configurations on next.config.js

What is the new behavior?
When users try to access OSS page and txt files on the old URL, they will be redirected to /docs/ path.
